<paragraph id="D5627A1B59EE7A3E247527E6A07BC4AF" pageId="0" pageNumber="121">Holotype.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="F84198B8872B75FB946B7241553446B4" pageId="0" pageNumber="121">China, Henan Province, Nanyang City, the Baotianman Nature Reserve, in rotting wood under a mixed forest, August 2016, K.F. Liu &amp; Z.W. Xi (holotype NYNU 168114T, ex-holotype CBS 14703).</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="83C54F70EFA9D13D708EE1E975F7C8F3" pageId="0" pageNumber="121" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="AEA201C64574A3FB61E2F59BB7DA4B09" pageId="0" pageNumber="121">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="61B8469EB816275262A9F55252F163F5" pageId="0" pageNumber="121">
The specific epithet 
<taxonomicName id="1F2200009B23A64032C12C3D5D208287" authorityName="C. Y. Chai &amp; F. L. Hui" authorityYear="2022" class="Saccharomycetes" family="Saccharomycetaceae" genus="Kodamaea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Kodamaea yamadae" order="Saccharomycetales" pageId="0" pageNumber="121" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="yamadae">
<emphasis id="13E011B7BC489600D144019C07B5BA88" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="121">Kodamaea yamadae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is used in honour of Y. Yamada for his proposal of the genus 
<taxonomicName id="596AE21F2173FB369A837B0546C2E70B" class="Saccharomycetes" family="Saccharomycetaceae" genus="Kodamaea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Kodamaea" order="Saccharomycetales" pageId="0" pageNumber="121" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="16B6A4DCA13727AF81311CC4018F6E17" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="121">Kodamaea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C35125B4997884FD48291A4B691EB9BD" pageId="0" pageNumber="121" type="description">
<paragraph id="FA23132AD98E5CC635E636996E232689" pageId="0" pageNumber="121">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="76AD670C0C52A4D84F3FAEE9BC136974" pageId="0" pageNumber="121">
In YM broth, after three days at 25 °C, cells are ellipsoidal to elongate (2-3 
<normalizedToken id="09ABC6CDE7549841F882371BEB520F45" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
4.5-10 
<normalizedToken id="0FFADE6FBDD0D44CEFE1BB759890DE8C" originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
) and occur singly or in pairs (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="461E9C463DA826445D54F7A208C2BEC5" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Morphology of Kodamaea yamadae (NYNU 168114, holotype) a budding cells in YM broth after 3 d b pseudohyphae on CM agar after 14 d. Scale bars: 10 μm." figureDoi="10.3897/mycokeys.89.81119.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/678672" pageId="0" pageNumber="121">4a</figureCitation>
). Sediment is formed after a month, but a pellicle is not observed. On YM agar, after 3 days at 25 °C, colonies are white, convex, sometimes fringed, glabrous or membranous, smooth or rugose and butyrous to tough due to filamentous growth. On Dalmau plate culture on CM agar, a rudimentary pseudomycelium is formed (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="32629C3B2CE46FFB6E40493F17867006" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Morphology of Kodamaea yamadae (NYNU 168114, holotype) a budding cells in YM broth after 3 d b pseudohyphae on CM agar after 14 d. Scale bars: 10 μm." figureDoi="10.3897/mycokeys.89.81119.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/678672" pageId="0" pageNumber="121">4b</figureCitation>
). Asci or signs of conjugation are not seen on sporulation media. Glucose, maltose, sucrose, trehalose and cellobiose are fermented but not galactose, melibiose, lactose, melezitose, raffinose, inulin or xylose. Glucose, galactose, glucosamine, d-ribose, d-xylose, sucrose, maltose, trehalose, methyl 
<normalizedToken id="A7C3986311F49A25910E60D34E9EC5FA" originalValue="α-d-glucoside">α-d-glucoside</normalizedToken>
, cellobiose, salicin, inulin, glycerol, erythritol, ribitol, d-glucitol, d-mannitol, d-glucono-1, 5-lactone, 2-keto-d-gluconate, succinate, citrate and ethanol are assimilated as sole carbon sources. l-sorbose, d-arabinose, l-arabinose, l-rhamnose, arbutin, melibiose, lactose, raffinose, melezitose, xylitol, galactitol, 
<emphasis id="9B9A1F58DFDED56ADBAF71CEECE19115" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="121">myo</emphasis>
-inositol, 5-keto-d-gluconate, d-gluconate, d-glucuronate, dl-lactate and methanol are not assimilated. Ethylamine, l-lysine, creatine, glucosamine and d-tryptophan are assimilated as sole nitrogen sources. Nitrate, nitrite, cadaverine, creatinine and imidazole are not assimilated. Growth is observed at 30 °C but not at 35 °C. Growth in the presence of 0.1% cycloheximide is positive, but growth in the presence of 10% NaCl plus 5% glucose and 1% acetic acid is negative. Starch-like compounds are not produced. Urease activity and diazonium blue B reactions are negative.
</paragraph>
<caption id="28B7259243BAD2DACB513FA932FE82F1" doi="10.3897/mycokeys.89.81119.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/678672" pageId="0" pageNumber="121" start="Figure 4" startId="F4">
<paragraph id="8BD65C6C860ABF31F782A334B4F84E1E" pageId="0" pageNumber="121">
<emphasis id="AAFBE0C8BBAA77A45FE7A90F71EB297A" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="121">Figure 4.</emphasis>
Morphology of 
<taxonomicName id="4E56470E7D75CE7511CB2B45BA2FBF46" authorityName="C. Y. Chai &amp; F. L. Hui" authorityYear="2022" class="Saccharomycetes" family="Saccharomycetaceae" genus="Kodamaea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Kodamaea yamadae" order="Saccharomycetales" pageId="0" pageNumber="121" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="yamadae">
<emphasis id="5016C166F36E27B9D1FC4315592F6A41" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="121">Kodamaea yamadae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(NYNU 168114, holotype) 
<emphasis id="188BE71B0F033C6FB4F870482B48CA16" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="121">a</emphasis>
budding cells in YM broth after 3 d 
<emphasis id="A4E0EABCF30554E49E600CF4C069A688" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="121">b</emphasis>
pseudohyphae on CM agar after 14 d. Scale bars: 10 
<normalizedToken id="6DACE0470E504326B4ED63935A0459FC" originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
.
</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="D49D511B1A8294A615B7C334CEE15EB5" pageId="0" pageNumber="121" type="additional isolates examined">
<paragraph id="4E6C2DC0148F9A89F357A3CB5C9EC98B" pageId="0" pageNumber="121">Additional isolates examined.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="F754419A689F00755816EC92F220155E" pageId="0" pageNumber="121">China, Henan Province, Nanyang City, the Baotianman Nature Reserve, in rotting wood under an oak forest, August 2016, K.F. Liu &amp; Z.W. Xi (NYNU 16858).</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="79137F00EEBE5D991A1A77FF3C72CB53" pageId="0" pageNumber="121" type="notes">
<paragraph id="8E42423D176DEB5751ECE95B2128EB6D" pageId="0" pageNumber="121">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5F3093B1547A11F6CFCBF14C07CA5DE8" pageId="0" pageNumber="121">
Two strains NYNU 16858 and NYNU 168114, representing 
<taxonomicName id="4A2F10F09F417C6F4A407A71F04EB666" genus="K." lsidName="K. yamadae" pageId="0" pageNumber="121" rank="species" species="yamadae">
<emphasis id="E6AC9FE3FA46EB8371A7119C664413DA" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="121">K. yamadae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
clustered in a well-supported clade that is closely related to 
<taxonomicName id="00C791F621C5C2D15950F20EF161DA4C" genus="K." lsidName="K. jinghongensis" pageId="0" pageNumber="121" rank="species" species="jinghongensis">
<emphasis id="F01B566493BCDBB77769B5B595BFAB80" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="121">K. jinghongensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="E4E7337EF548C62E2C1E9EFAA8F9C0B3" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1099/ijsem.0.002117" author="Gao, WL" journalOrPublisher="International Journal of Systematic and Evolutionary Microbiology" pageId="0" pageNumber="121" pagination="3358 - 3362" refId="B5" refString="Gao, WL, Liu, TT, Zheng, J, Hui, FL, 2017. Kodamaea neixiangensis f.a., sp. nov. and Kodamaea jinghongensis f.a., sp. nov., two yeast species isolated from rotting wood. International Journal of Systematic and Evolutionary Microbiology 67 (9): 3358 - 3362, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1099/ijsem.0.002117" title="Kodamaea neixiangensis f. a., sp. nov. and Kodamaea jinghongensis f. a., sp. nov., two yeast species isolated from rotting wood." url="https://doi.org/10.1099/ijsem.0.002117" volume="67" year="2017">Gao et al. 2017</bibRefCitation>
) and 
<taxonomicName id="DF9BFFE8FB5FBFF817D25CED08DB81EA" genus="K." lsidName="K. fukazawae" pageId="0" pageNumber="121" rank="species" species="fukazawae">
<emphasis id="8373139C7321299BC4D87ABF678B80D2" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="121">K. fukazawae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="8C81B05709C8EFF19C42D9F7854EFD83" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1007/BF02461023" author="Nakase, T" journalOrPublisher="Mycoscience" pageId="0" pageNumber="121" pagination="465 - 476" refId="B20" refString="Nakase, T, Suzuki, M, Sugita, T, Suh, SO, Komagata, K, 1999. Three new species of anamorphic yeasts phenotypically and phylogenetically related to Candida mesenterica: The description of Candida fungicola sp. nov., Candida sagamina sp. nov., and Candida fukazawae sp. nov. isolated from fruit bodies of mushrooms. Mycoscience 40 (6): 465 - 476, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1007/BF02461023" title="Three new species of anamorphic yeasts phenotypically and phylogenetically related to Candida mesenterica: The description of Candida fungicola sp. nov., Candida sagamina sp. nov., and Candida fukazawae sp. nov. isolated from fruit bodies of mushrooms." url="https://doi.org/10.1007/BF02461023" volume="40" year="1999">Nakase et al. 1999</bibRefCitation>
). The nucleotide differences between 
<taxonomicName id="471AD9B11B33D5D1CA6D61088BF5CB7D" genus="K." lsidName="K. yamadae" pageId="0" pageNumber="121" rank="species" species="yamadae">
<emphasis id="64EE5703554B15CE33746412C8356E12" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="121">K. yamadae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="CC674B3439CD3721C4EB7FC00B60F844" genus="K." lsidName="K. jinghongensis" pageId="0" pageNumber="121" rank="species" species="jinghongensis">
<emphasis id="676DEED2AE93B9C1977EA751FFCE48B7" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="121">K. jinghongensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were 2.8% substitutions in the LSU rDNA sequences and 3.9% substitutions in the ITS region. Similarly, 
<taxonomicName id="0281BF272B0CE40A16B13ABE6B5C640E" genus="K." lsidName="K. yamadae" pageId="0" pageNumber="121" rank="species" species="yamadae">
<emphasis id="677450FF90F4825D7D7EE4BDEEBD6BB5" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="121">K. yamadae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="18FFA1159ECE8CD3C0DD5A753799D532" genus="K." lsidName="K. fukazawae" pageId="0" pageNumber="121" rank="species" species="fukazawae">
<emphasis id="9B7E267506782BBF3F75575411CE3237" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="121">K. fukazawae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
showed differences of 2.6% substitutions in the LSU rDNA sequences and 4.7% substitutions in the ITS region. Physiologically, the novel species differed from 
<taxonomicName id="E13101E046F992BF637DA7230C5E5CC4" genus="K." lsidName="K. jinghongensis" pageId="0" pageNumber="121" rank="species" species="jinghongensis">
<emphasis id="8E1BE36DD5BA4BB7A2E9D9AEA1E6D477" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="121">K. jinghongensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by its ability to ferment cellobiose and its inability to assimilate arbutin. Unlike 
<taxonomicName id="7951680B02FB5A6A29E033B8B833349B" genus="K." lsidName="K. fukazawae" pageId="0" pageNumber="121" rank="species" species="fukazawae">
<emphasis id="9CDE407307225ADD14F1A5A2EB66A874" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="121">K. fukazawae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the novel species was able to assimilate d-galactose, l-sorbose, inulin, d-arabinose, l-arabinose, l-rhamnose, and methanol, and was not able to grow in the presence of 0.1% cycloheximide. In all cases, identification by sequencing was the best approach.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
